<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_trig_prop" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Trigonometric functions: properties</title>
<objectives>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                Derive algebraic and graphical properties of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> from their unit circle definitions.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Introduce the remaining trigonometric functions <m>\tan</m>, <m>\cot</m>, <m>\sec</m>, and <m>\csc</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Learn to give detailed sketches of trigonometric functions. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Solve equations involving trigonometric functions.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
</objectives>
<subsection xml:id="ss_props_cos_sine">
<title>Properties of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m></title>
<p>
    <xref ref="d_sine_cosine"/> ties the values of <m>\cos\theta</m> and <m>\sin\theta</m> intimately to the geometry of the unit circle with defining equation <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>. As a result we can easily prove some useful properties about <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m>, and their relationship to one another. 
</p>
<theorem xml:id="th_sin_cos_props">
<title>Properties of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
<ol>
    <li>
        <title>Pythagorean identity</title>
        <p>
            <md number="yes">
            <mrow xml:id="eq_pythag_ident"> \cos^2\theta+\sin^2\theta=1 </mrow>
            </md>
            for all <m>\theta\in \R</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <title>Periodicity</title>
        <p>
            <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> are periodic with period <m>2\pi</m>: <ie/>,
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>\cos(\theta+2\pi) \amp =\cos \theta \amp \sin(\theta+2\pi)\amp =\sin\theta</mrow>
            </md>
            for all <m>\theta\in \R</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <title>Range of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m></title>
        <p>
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>\range \cos \amp =\range \sin =[-1,1]</mrow>
            </md>.
            In particular, we have 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow xml:id="eq_trig_bound_elem"> -1 \amp \leq \cos\theta\leq 1 \amp -1\amp \leq \sin\theta\leq 1</mrow>
            </md>
            for all <m>\theta\in \R</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <title>Even/odd properties</title>
        <p>
            <md number="yes">
            <mrow xml:id="eq_even_odd"> \cos(-\theta) \amp = \cos\theta \amp \sin(-\theta)\amp = -\sin\theta</mrow>
            </md>
            for all <m>\theta\in \R</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <title>Cofunction identities</title>
        <p>
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow> \cos\theta\amp =\sin(\pi/2-\theta)  \amp \sin\theta\amp = \cos(\pi/2-\theta)</mrow>
            </md>
            for all <m>\theta\in \R</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                The Pythagorean idenity follows almost immediately from the definition of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m>. Given any angle <m>\theta</m>, let <m>P=(x,y)</m> be the point where the terminal edge of <m>\theta</m> intersects the unit circle. By definition of the unit circle, <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> satisfy <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>. By definition of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m>, on the other hand, we have <m>\cos\theta=x</m> and <m>\sin\theta=y</m>. We conclude that <m>\cos^2\theta+\sin^2\theta=1</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                For any <m>\theta\in \R</m>, the two angles <m>\theta</m> and <m>\theta+2\pi</m> are coterminal. As a result, both angles are associated to the same point <m>P=(x,y)</m>, following the recipe of <xref ref="d_sine_cosine"/>. We conclude that 
                <md>
                    <mrow>\cos\theta \amp = \cos(\theta+2\pi)=x</mrow>
                    <mrow>\sin\theta \amp =\sin(\theta+2\pi)=y</mrow>
                </md>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Given any <m>\theta\in \R</m>, we have <m>\cos\theta=x</m> and <m>\sin\theta=y</m>, where <m>P=(x,y)</m> is a certain point on the unit circle. Since  by definition of the unit circle these coordinates satisfy <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>, it is easy to see that we must have <m>\abs{x}\leq 1</m> and <m>\abs{y}\leq 1</m>, or equivalently, 
                <md>
                    <mrow>-1 \amp \leq x\leq 1 \amp -1\amp \leq y\leq 1</mrow>
                </md>.
                We conclude that <m>-1\leq \cos\theta\leq 1</m> and <m>-1\leq \sin\theta\leq 1</m> for all <m>\theta\in \R</m>, and thus <m>\range \cos\subseteq [-1,1]</m> and <m>\range \sin\subseteq [-1,1]</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                We now show that in fact we have <m>\range \cos=\range\sin=[-1,1]</m>. Given any <m>a\in [-1,1]</m>, since <m>\abs{a}\leq 1</m>,we may define <m>b=\sqrt{1-a^2}</m>. Since <m>b^2=1-a^2</m>, it is easy to see that <m>b\in [0,1]</m> and that 
                <md>
                    <mrow>a^2+b^2 \amp = a^2+(1-a^2)=1</mrow>
                </md>.
                Thus <m>P=(a,b)</m> is a point on the unit circle. Letting <m>\theta</m> be the central angle in standard position subtended by the arc from <m>(1,0)</m> to <m>P</m>, we see that <m>\cos\theta=a</m>. This proves <m>\range \cos=[-1,1]</m>. A similar argument shows that <m>\range \sin=[-1,1]</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Adding a suitable multiple of <m>2\pi</m> and using periodicity, we may assume that <m>\theta\in [0,2\pi]</m> and <m>-\theta\in [-2\pi,0]</m>. Let <m>P=(x,y)</m> be the point where the terminal edge of <m>\theta</m> intersects the unit circe, and let <m>P'=(x',y')</m> be the point where the terminal edge of <m>-\theta</m> intersects the intersection of the unit circle. The oriented arc associated to <m>\theta</m> starts from <m>(1,0)</m>, moves counterclockwise and ends at <m>P</m>; the oriented arc associated to <m>-\theta</m> traverses the same length of the circle (since <m>\abs{\theta}=\abs{-\theta}</m>) starting from <m>(1,0)</m>, but in the clockwise direction. It follows that the latter arc is just the reflection of the former arc across the <m>x</m>-axis.  As a result we have <m>x'=x</m> and <m>y'=-y</m>. We conclude that 
                <md>
                    <mrow>\cos(-\theta) \amp = x'=x\cos\theta</mrow>
                    <mrow>\sin(-\theta) \amp = y'=-y=-\sin\theta</mrow>
                </md>.
            </p>
            <image width="75%">
                <shortdescription>Unit circle picture of theta and minus theta</shortdescription>
                <sageplot>
var('t')
c(t)=(cos(t),sin(t))
P=point([c(3*pi/4),c(-3*pi/4)], size=50, color='blue')
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,0,2*pi), color='blue')
L1=line([(0,0),c(3*pi/4)], color='blue', thickness=2)
L2=line([(0,0),c(-3*pi/4)], color='blue', thickness=2)
arc1=parametric_plot(.2*c(3*pi/4*t),(t,0,1), color='red')
arc2=parametric_plot(.2*c(-3*pi/4*t),(t,0,1), color='green')
t1=text(r"$\theta$",.3*c(3*pi/8),color="black", fontsize=16)
t2=text(r"$-\theta$",.3*c(-3*pi/8),color="black", fontsize=16)
t3=text(r"$P=(x,y)$",1.25*c(3*pi/4),color="black",fontsize=16)
t4=text(r"$P'=(-x,y)$",1.25*c(-3*pi/4),color="black",fontsize=16)
C+P+arc1+arc2+t1+t2+t3+t4+L1+L2
                </sageplot>
            </image>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                We will prove <m>\cos\theta=\sin(\pi/2-\theta)</m> for all <m>\theta</m>. It then follows that
                <md number="yes">
                    <mrow> \cos(\pi/2-\theta) \amp = \sin(\pi/2-(\pi/2-\theta)) </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \sin \theta</mrow>
                </md>.
                Given any <m>\theta\in \R</m>, adding a suitable multiple of <m>2\pi</m> and using periodicity, we may assume that <m>\theta\in [0,2\pi]</m>. If <m>\theta\in [\pi,2\pi]</m>, then <m>-\theta</m> is coterminal to an angle in <m>[0,\pi]</m>. Since <m>\cos(-\theta)=-\cos\theta</m> and <m>\sin(\pi-(-\theta))=\sin(\pi+\theta)=-\sin\theta</m>, we see that <m>\cos\theta=\sin(\pi/2-\theta)</m> if and only if <m>\cos(-\theta)=\sin(\pi/2-(-\theta))</m>. Thus we may assume that <m>\theta\in [0,\pi]</m>. Since, furthermore, the result is easily verified for <m>\theta=0</m> and <m>\theta=\pi</m>, we assume that <m>\theta\in (0,\pi)</m>. Let <m>P=(x,y)</m> be the point where the terminal edge of <m>\theta</m> intersects the unit circle, and let <m>T</m> be the corresponding reference triangle with vertices <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>P</m>, and <m>(x,0)</m> obtained by dropping the perpendicular from <m>P</m> to the <m>x</m>-axis.
            </p>
            <p>
                Consider the the case where <m>\theta</m> is acute: <ie/>, <m>\theta\in (0,\pi/2)</m>. In this case the angle of <m>T</m> at <m>(0,0)</m> is <m>\theta</m> and the angle of <m>T</m> at <m>P</m> is <m>\pi/2-\theta</m>, since <m>T</m> is a right triangle. Using triangular interpretations of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m>, we conclude that 
                <md>
                    <mrow>\sin(\pi/2-\theta) \amp = \frac{x}{1}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \cos\theta</mrow>
                </md>,
                as desired. 
            </p>
            <p>
                The case for <m>\theta</m> obtuse (<ie/>, <m>\theta\in (\pi/2, 2\pi)</m>) is similar, with some sign details. The point <m>P=(x,y)</m> is now in the second quadrant of the plane, which means the <m>x</m>-coordinate is <em>negative</em>.  Now the angle at <m>(0,0)</m> is <m>\pi-\theta</m>, and the angle at <m>P</m> is <m>\pi/2-(\pi-\theta)=\theta-\pi/2</m>. The same triangular reasoning as above can be applied, but now we have to be careful about sign: we have <m>\sin(\theta-\pi/2)=\abs{x}=-x</m> in this case, since <m>x\leq 0</m>. Using the oddness of sine, we conclude that <m>\sin(\pi/2-\theta)=x</m>, as desired! 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<p>
    The interdependence of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> articulated in <xref ref="th_sin_cos_props"/>, allows us in many situations to derive the value of one of the two function <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> from the other, at least up to sign. The next example illustrates this idea. 
</p>
<example xml:id="eg_cos_sin_props">
<title>Interdependence of <m>cos</m> and <m>\sin</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
For a fixed but indeterminate angle <m>\theta</m>, information about one of the two values <m>\cos\theta</m> and <m>\sin\theta</m> is given. If possible, determine the value of the other function; if not, explain why the exact value cannot be determined.
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\cos\theta=-1/3</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\sin\theta=2/5</m> and <m>\theta\in [pi/2, 3\pi/2]</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\cos(\pi/2-\theta)=0.78</m>
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            Using the Pythagorean identity, we can attempt to solve for <m>\sin\theta</m>: 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>\cos^2\theta+\sin^2\theta \amp =1</mrow>
                <mrow>(-1/3)^2+\sin^2\theta \amp = 1</mrow>
                <mrow>\sin^2\theta \amp = 1-1/9=8/9</mrow>
                <mrow>\sin\theta \amp = \pm\sqrt{8/9} = \pm\frac{2\sqrt{2}}{3}</mrow>
            </md>.
            We see that there are two possible values of <m>\sin\theta</m>. Without further information, we cannot determine which one applies in the given situation. Indeed, there are two separate points <m>P=(-1/3, 2\sqrt{2}/3)</m> and <m>Q=(-1/3,-2\sqrt{2}/3)</m> on the unit circle with <m>x</m>-coordinates equal to <m>-1/3</m>. Letting <m>\theta</m> be the angle associated to <m>P</m>, we have <m>\cos\theta=-1/3</m> and <m>\sin\theta=2\sqrt{2}/3</m>. Similarly, letting <m>\theta</m> be the angle associated to <m>Q</m>, we have <m>\cos\theta=-1/3</m> and <m>\sin\theta=-2\sqrt{2}/3</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Using the Pythagorean identity, we can attempt to solve for <m>\cos\theta</m>: 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>\cos^2\theta+\sin^2\theta \amp =1</mrow>
                <mrow>\cos^2\theta+(2/5)^2 \amp = 1</mrow>
                <mrow>\cos^2\theta \amp = 1-4/25=21/25</mrow>
                <mrow>\cos\theta \amp = \pm\sqrt{21/25}=\pm\frac{\sqrt{21}}{5}</mrow>
            </md>.
            Again, we so far only know <m>\cos\theta</m> up to sign. However, since <m>\theta\in [pi/2, 3\pi/2]</m>, the point associated to <m>\theta</m> is in the second or third quadrant of the plane, where the <m>x</m>-coordinate is always negative. (See <xref ref="fig_sign_coord_unit_circle"/>.) We conclude that <m>\cos\theta=-\frac{\sqrt{21}}{5}</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Using the cofunction identity, we conclude immediately that 
            <md>
                <mrow>\sin \theta \amp =\cos(\pi/2-\theta)=0.78</mrow>
            </md>.

        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</solution>
</example>

</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="ss_graph_sin_cos">
<title>Graphs of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m></title>
<p>
    The properties of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> spelled out in <xref ref="th_sin_cos_props"/> are readily interpreted visually in terms of the graphs of these two functions. For example, the fact that <m>\range\cos=\range\sin=[-1,1]</m> tells us that the <m>y</m>-coordinates of points on the these graphs always lie between <m>-1</m> and <m>1</m>, and furthermore that every value in that range is the <m>y</m>-value of some point on the graph. Next, the fact that <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> both have period <m>2\pi</m> tells us that once we know what the graph looks like over the interval <m>[0,2\pi]</m> (or any interval of length <m>2\pi</m>), we can produce the rest of the graph by <q>cutting and pasting</q>: in more detail, take the graph of the function over <m>[0,2\pi]</m> and simply shift to the right by <m>2\pi</m> to get the graph over <m>[2\pi, 4\pi]</m>; similarly, shift to the left by <m>2\pi</m> to get the graph over <m>[-2\pi, 0]</m>. Lastly, the even/odd properties of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> tell us the usual symmetry properties of graphs of even and odd functions. (See <xref ref="d_even_odd"/> and the discussion that follows it.)
</p>
<p>
    But what exactly does the graph of one these functions look like for <m>x\in [0,2\pi]</m>. We can give a fairly precise qualitative description of this by examining what happens to the <m>x</m>-coordinate of the point <m>P_\theta</m> associated to the central angle <m>\theta</m>, as we let <m>\theta</m> range from <m>0</m> to <m>2\pi</m>. It is useful to think of this as an animation, where the point <m>P_\theta</m> associated to <m>\theta</m> travels all the way around the unit circle as we <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>0</m> to <m>2\pi</m>. Focusing just on the <m>x</m>-coordinate of <m>P_\theta</m>, we deduce the following qualitative summary. 
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                As <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>0</m> to <m>\pi/2</m>, the <m>x</m>-coordinate of <m>P_\theta</m> decreases from <m>1</m> to <m>0</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                As <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>\pi/2</m> to <m>\pi</m>, the <m>x</m>-coordinate of <m>P_\theta</m> decreases from <m>0</m> to <m>-1</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                As <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>\pi</m> to <m>3\pi/2</m>, the <m>x</m>-coordinate of <m>P_\theta</m> increases from <m>-1</m> to <m>0</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                As <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>3\pi/2</m> to <m>2\pi</m>, the <m>x</m>-coordinate of <m>P_\theta</m> increases from <m>0</m> to <m>1</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
    Remembering that <m>\cos \theta</m> is by definition the <m>x</m>-coordinate of this point <m>P_\theta</m>, our summary above leads pretty directly to the graph of <m>\cos\theta</m> below. We have enhanced this sketch with some actual plotted points: namely, the point <m>(\theta, \cos\theta)</m>, for each of the 16 familiar angles from <xref ref="fig_unit_circle_familiar"/>. 
</p>
<figure xml:id="fig_graph_cos">
    <caption>Graph of <m>\cos</m> including points <m>(\theta, \cos\theta)</m> for familiar angles.</caption>
    <image width="75%">
        <shortdescription>Graph of cosine with some plotted points</shortdescription>
        <sageplot>
costicks=[n*pi/4 for n in range(-2,10)]
costicks_labels=[r"$\frac{"+str(n)+r"\pi}{4}$" for n in range(-2,9)]
f(t)=cos(t)
cosG=plot(f(x),x,-pi/2,5*pi/2,ticks=[costicks,[-1,-.5,.5,1]], tick_formatter=[[r"$-\frac{\pi}{2}$",r"$-\frac{\pi}{4}$","",r"$\frac{\pi}{4}$",r"$\frac{\pi}{2}$",r"$\frac{3\pi}{4}$",r"$\pi$",r"$\frac{5\pi}{4}$",r"$\frac{3\pi}{2}$",r"$\frac{7\pi}{4}$", r"$2\pi$",r"$\frac{9\pi}{4}$"],["$-1$",r"$-\frac{1}{2}$",r"$\frac{1}{2}$",r"$1$"]], ymin=-1.25, ymax=1.25)
P=points([(t,f(t)) for t in [n*pi/6 for n in range(12)]+[n*pi/4 for n in range(8)]], size=50, color='red')
cosG+P
        </sageplot>      
    </image>
</figure>
<p>
    A similar description can be obtained for the graph of <m>\sin</m> by looking at the <m>y</m>-coordinates of the points <m>P_\theta</m> as <m>\theta</m> ranges from <m>0</m> to <m>2\pi</m>. These values begin at <m>0</m>, increase to <m>1</m> as <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>0</m> to <m>\pi/2</m>, decrease back to <m>0</m> as <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>\pi/2</m> to <m>\pi</m>, decrease further to <m>-1</m> as <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>\pi</m> to <m>3\pi/2</m>, and finally increase back to <m>0</m> as <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>3\pi/2</m> to <m>2\pi</m>. Identifying this changing <m>y</m>-value of <m>P_\theta</m> with <m>\sin\theta</m>, we obtain the following graph. 
</p>
<figure xml:id="fig_graph_sine">
    <caption>Graph of <m>\sin</m> including points <m>(\theta, \sin\theta)</m> for familiar angles.</caption>
    <image width="75%">
        <shortdescription>Graph of sine with some plotted points</shortdescription>
        <sageplot>
costicks=[n*pi/4 for n in range(-2,10)]
costicks_labels=[r"$\frac{"+str(n)+r"\pi}{4}$" for n in range(-2,9)]
f(t)=sin(t)
cosG=plot(f(x),x,-pi/2,5*pi/2,ticks=[costicks,[-1,-.5,.5,1]], tick_formatter=[[r"$-\frac{\pi}{2}$",r"$-\frac{\pi}{4}$","",r"$\frac{\pi}{4}$",r"$\frac{\pi}{2}$",r"$\frac{3\pi}{4}$",r"$\pi$",r"$\frac{5\pi}{4}$",r"$\frac{3\pi}{2}$",r"$\frac{7\pi}{4}$", r"$2\pi$",r"$\frac{9\pi}{4}$"],["$-1$",r"$-\frac{1}{2}$",r"$\frac{1}{2}$",r"$1$"]], ymin=-1.25, ymax=1.25)
P=points([(t,f(t)) for t in [n*pi/6 for n in range(12)]+[n*pi/4 for n in range(8)]], size=50, color='red')
cosG+P
        </sageplot>
        
    </image>
</figure>
<p>
    Understanding the basic pattern of the changing values of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> allows us to quickly give a detailed sketch of these functions. Incorporating our shifting and scaling techniques, it is then not difficult to obtain the graphs of more general functions of the form 
    <md>
        <mrow>f(\theta) \amp =A\cos(k\theta)+B \amp g(\theta)\amp=A\sin(k\theta)+B</mrow>
    </md>,
    where <m>A,B,k</m> are fixed constants. Such functions are called <term>sinusoidal</term>. Here is a summary of these parameters affect the graphs of the functions. We work from the inner most operation (multiplying <m>x</m> by <m>k</m>) to the outermost (adding <m>B</m>)
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                Assume <m>k&gt; 0</m>. Scaling the input <m>\theta</m> by <m>k</m> shrinks the graph of <m>\cos</m> horizontally by <m>1/k</m>. As a result, the period of the functions <m>f(\theta)=\cos k\theta</m> and  <m>g(\theta)=\sin k\theta</m> is <m>2\pi/k</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Since scaling by <m>A</m> scales the <m>y</m>-values of the graph of <m>\cos</m> or <m>\sin</m> by a factor of <m>A</m>, the functions <m>f(\theta)=A\cos k\theta</m> and <m>g(\theta)=A\sin k\theta</m> vary (or <term>oscillate</term>) between <m>-A</m> and <m>A</m>. Accordingly, <m>\abs{A}</m> is called the <term>amplitude</term> of the the functions <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>. The amplitude measures how much the <m>y</m>-values vary from midline <m>y=0</m> of the graph of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Lastly, the parameter <m>B</m> shifts the graph vertically by <m>B</m>. As a result, the midline of the functions <m>f(\theta)=A\cos k\theta+B</m> and <m>g(\theta)=A\sin k \theta+B</m> is shifted from <m>y=0</m> to <m>y=B</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
The foregoing gives us the following general procedure for producing a detailed graph of a sinusoidal function. 
</p>
<algorithm xml:id="proc_sinusoidal">
    <title>Graphing sinusoidal functions</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>f(\theta)=A\cos k \theta+B</m> and <m>g(\theta)=A\sin k\theta+B</m>, where <m>A</m> and <m>k</m> are positive constants, and <m>B</m> is any constant. To produce a graph of <m>f</m> and/or <m>g</m>, proceed as follows. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <title>Determine period</title>
                    <p>
                        The period of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> is <m>2\pi/k</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Midline and amplitude</title>
        
                    <p>
                        The midline of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> is the horizontal line <m>y=B</m>. The amplitude of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> is <m>\abs{A}=A</m>, which means the <m>y</m>-values of these functions vary between <m>B-A</m> and <m>B+A</m>. Draw the dotted lines <m>y=B-A</m>, <m>y=B</m>, and <m>y=B+A</m> on your coordinate plane. These will help scaffold your graph of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>, as they indicate the bottom, middle, and top of the graph. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Divide period into fourths and plot</title>
                    <p>
                       Divide the fundamental period interval <m>[0,2\pi/k]</m> into 4 equal subintervals 
                       <md>
                        <mrow>0\amp &lt; 2\pi/4k &lt; \pi/k&lt; 3\pi/4k &lt; 2\pi/k
                        </mrow>
                       </md>.
                       The functions <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are monotonic on each subinterval. Plot the 5 points with inputs 
                       <md>
                        <mrow>0,\frac{\pi}{2k},\frac{\pi}{k},\frac{3\pi}{2k},\frac{2\pi}{k}</mrow>
                       </md>
                       and connect them with smooth curves to produce a graph of <m>f</m> and/or <m>g</m> over <m>[0,2\pi/k]</m>. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In the given situation, where <m>A</m> and <m>k</m> are both <em>positive</em>, the <m>y</m>-values of these 5 plotted points follow the bottom/middle/top patterns below. 
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    For <m>f(\theta)=A\cos k \theta+B</m>, the points follow the <q>cosine</q> pattern: top-middle-bottom-middle-top.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    For <m>g(\theta)=A\sin k \theta+B</m>, the points follow the <q>sine</q> pattern: middle-top-middle-bottom-middle.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Cut and paste</title>
                    <p>
                        Extend the graph horizontally as much as you like by shifting the graph for <m>\theta\in [0,2\pi/k]</m> to the right and/or left by integer multiples of <m>2\pi/k</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
</algorithm>
<remark>
    <title>Graphing sinusoidal functions</title>
    <p>
        We assume <m>A</m> and <m>k</m> are positive in <xref ref="proc_sinusoidal"/> only for convenience. The case where either one of these parameters is negative can be derived from the positive case by making use of an appropriate reflection: either through the midline <m>y=B</m> (if <m>A</m> is negative), or through the <m>y</m>-axis (if <m>k</m> is negative). 
    </p>
    <p>
        In the case where <m>A</m> is negative, the cosine and sine patterns described in Step 3 of <xref ref="proc_sinusoidal"/> are flipped about the midline. In more detail, if <m>A&lt;0 </m>, then the 5 plotted points of <m>f</m> follow the <q>negative cosine pattern</q> (bottom-middle-top-middle-bottom), and the 5 plotted points of <m>g</m> follow the <q>negative sine pattern</q> (middle-bottom-middle-top-middle).
    </p>
</remark>
<example xml:id="eg_sinusoidal">
<title>Graphing sinusoidal functions</title>
<statement>
<p>
Produce a detailed graph of <m>f(t)=3\cos(t/2)-1</m> following <xref ref="proc_sinusoidal"/>.
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
In this case we have <m>A=3</m>, <m>k=1/2</m>, and <m>B=-1</m>. It follows that the period of <m>f</m> is <m>2\pi/(1/2)=4\pi</m>, the midline is <m>y=-1</m>, and the <m>y</m>-values of the graph of <m>f</m> oscillate between <m>y=-1-3=-4</m> and <m>y=-1+3=2</m>.

</p>
<p>
    We divide the period interval <m>[0,4\pi]</m> into <m>4</m> equal subintervals and plot points with inputs <m>0,\pi, 2\pi, 3\pi, 4\pi</m>. Since <m>f</m> is defined in terms of <m>\cos</m>, these plotted points follow the top-middle-bottom-middle-top <q>cosine pattern</q>. Putting this all together, we obtain the graph in <xref ref="fig_graph_sinusoidal_cos"/>.
</p>
<figure xml:id="fig_graph_sinusoidal_cos">
    <caption>Graph of <m>f(t)=3\cos(t/2)-1</m></caption>
    <image width="75%">
        <shortdescription>Graph of 3 times cos(t/2)-1 with some plotted points</shortdescription>
        <sageplot>
f(x)=3*cos(x/2)-1
P=plot(f(x),x,-pi,5*pi, ticks=[[n*pi for n in range(-1,6)],[-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2]], tick_formatter=pi, ymin=-4.5, ymax=2.5)
L1=line([(-pi, -4), (5*pi, -4)], color='red', linestyle='dashed')
L2=line([(-pi, -1), (5*pi, -1)], color='red', linestyle='dashed')
L3=line([(-pi, 2), (5*pi, 2)], color='red', linestyle='dashed')
t1=text("$y=-4$", (pi/2, -4.15), color='black', fontsize=14)
t2=text("$y=-1$", (pi/2, -1.15), color='black', fontsize=14)
t3=text("$y=2$", (pi/2, 2.15), color='black', fontsize=14)
Q=point([(n*pi,f(n*pi)) for n in range(-1,6)], size=50, color='red')
P+L1+L2+L3+t1+t2+t3+Q
        </sageplot>
    </image>
</figure>
</solution>
</example>

</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="ss_six_trig_functions">
<title>The six trigonometric functions</title>
<p>
    In addition to <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m>, there are four additional standard trigonometric functions formed by taking simple algebraic combination. We introduce these now.
</p>
<definition xml:id="d_trig_funct">
<title>Trigonometric functions</title>
<statement>
<p>
The <term>trigonometric functions</term> are the six functions consisting of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m>, together with the following four functions. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <title>Tangent</title>
        
        
        <p>
           The <term>tangent function</term>, is defined as 
           <md number="yes">
            <mrow>\tan \theta \amp =\frac{\sin\theta}{\cos\theta}</mrow>
           </md>.
           The domain of <m>\tan</m> is <m>D=\{\theta\in \R\mid \theta\ne \pi/2+\pi n \text{ for } n\in \Z\}</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <title>Cotangent</title>
        <p>
            The <term>cotangent function</term> is defined as 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>\cot\theta \amp =\frac{1}{\tan\theta}=\frac{\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}</mrow>
            </md>.
            The domain of <m>\cot\theta</m> is <m>D=\{\theta\in \R\mid \theta\ne \pi n \text{ for } n\in \Z\}</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    
    <li>
        <title>Secant</title>
        <p>
            The <term>secant function</term> is defined as 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>\sec\theta \amp =\frac{1}{\cos\theta}</mrow>
            </md>.
            The domain of <m>\sec\theta</m> is <m>D=\{\theta\in \R\mid \theta\ne \pi/2+\pi n \text{ for } n\in \Z\}</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <title>Cosecant</title>
        <p>
            The <term>cosecant function</term> is defined as 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>\csc\theta \amp =\frac{1}{\sin\theta}</mrow>
            </md>.
            The domain of <m>\csc\theta</m> is <m>D=\{\theta\in \R\mid \theta\ne \pi n \text{ for } n\in \Z\}</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

</subsection>
<!--     
 <subsection>
    <title>Right-triangle trigonometry</title>
    <p>
      There is another standard approach to defining the trigonometric functions,
      at least for <em>acute</em> angles,
      meaning angles measure between <m>0^\circ</m> and <m>90^\circ</m>.
      Sine, cosine,
      and tangent can be defined in terms of side lengths of triangles.
      Every acute angle <m>\theta</m> can be realized as part of a right triangle with opposite and adjacent sides as labeled in <xref ref="fig_TaalmanPage402a">Figure</xref> below:
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig_TaalmanPage402a">
      <caption>Opposite and adjacent sides to an acute angle. The hypotenuse is opposite the right angle.</caption>
      <image width="42%" source="TaalmanPage402a.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
      For any given acute angle there are many possible right triangles that we could draw,
      but as illustrated in <xref ref="fig_TaalmanPage402b">Figure</xref>,
      all of the possibilities will have the same three angles and thus be similar triangles.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig_TaalmanPage402b">
      <caption>Right triangles with the same acute angles must be similar.</caption>
      <image width="42%" source="TaalmanPage402b.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
      This relationship is key,
      since the Law of Similar Triangles tells us that the similar triangles may have different side lengths,
      but always have the same <em>ratios</em> of side lengths:
      <me>
        \frac{a}{b} = \frac{A}{B},\qquad \frac{a}{c} = \frac{A}{C}, \qquad \frac{b}{c} = \frac{B}{C}
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      We have defined three of the functions that result from these ratios already:
      sine results from the ratio of the opposite side to the hypotenuse,
      cosine results from the ratio of the adjacent side to the hypotenuse,
      and tangent results from the ratio of the opposite side to the adjacent side.
      There are three other trigonometric functions that we have not yet mentioned that result from the reciprocals of these ratios:
      cosecant, secant, and cotangent, respectively.
    </p>
    <p>
      In the following definition, "opp," "adj," and "hyp" denote the lengths of the opposite side,
      adjacent side, and hypotenuse, respectively:
    </p>
    <definition>
      <title>Trigonometric functions for acute angles</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given an acute angle <m>\theta</m>,
          the six <em>trigonometric functions</em>
          are defined as the following six ratios of side lengths:
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\sin\theta = \frac{\text{ opp } }{\text{ hyp } }</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\csc\theta = \frac{\text{ hyp } }{\text{ opp } } = \frac{1}{\sin\theta}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\cos\theta = \frac{\text{ adj } }{\text{ hyp } }</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\sec\theta = \frac{\text{ hyp } }{\text{ adj } } = \frac{1}{\cos\theta}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\tan\theta = \frac{\text{ opp } }{\text{ adj } } = \frac{\sin\theta}{\cos\theta}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\cot\theta = \frac{\text{ adj } }{\text{ opp } } = \frac{\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
          It is worth noting in particular that
          <m>\cot\theta = \frac{1}{\tan\theta}</m> for most values of <m>\theta</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="ex_3-4-5">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For example,
          consider the angle <m>\theta</m> shown in the <m>3-4-5</m> right triangle shown below:
        </p>
        <p>
          The side lengths here are opp<m>=3</m>,
          adj<m>=4</m>, and hyp<m>=5</m>.
          The ratios of these side lengths give us
          <me>
            \sin\theta = \frac{3}{5},\cos\theta = \frac{4}{5},\tan\theta  = \frac{3}{4}
          </me>
          <me>
            \csc\theta = \frac{5}{3}, \sec\theta = \frac{5}{4},\cot\theta = \frac{4}{3}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The same angle <m>\theta</m> as in <xref ref="ex_3-4-5">Example</xref>
          can be thought of inside the <m>6-8-10</m> triangle:
        </p>
        <p>
          <image width="28%" source="TaalmanPage403ab.png"/>
        </p>
        <p>
          Although all the side lengths are twice as large,
          their ratios will be exactly the same.
          Find <m>\sin\theta</m>, <m>\cos\theta</m>,
          and <m>\tan\theta</m> using the side lengths in the <m>6-8-10</m> triangle,
          and simplify in order to verify that they are the same as in <xref ref="ex_3-4-5">Example</xref>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      The right-triangle definitions of sine,
      cosine and tangent for acute angles are compatible with the original definitions via the unit circle.
      Acute angles in standard position must terminate in the first quadrant,
      as illustrated below:
    </p>
    <p>
      <image width="37%" source="TaalmanPage406b.png"/>
    </p>
    <p>
      If the radius of the circle is 1, then the hypotenuse of the triangle is 1, and so we can see that
      <me>
        \sin\theta = \frac{\text{ opp } }{\text{ hyp } } = \frac{y}{1} = y
      </me>
      <me>
        \cos\theta =  \frac{\text{ adj } }{\text{ hyp } } = \frac{x}{1} = x
      </me>
      <me>
        \tan\theta = \frac{\text{ opp } }{\text{ adj } } = \frac{y}{x} = \frac{\sin\theta}{\cos\theta}
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      The functions cosecant, secant,
      and cotangent are defined for arbitrary angles as the reciprocals of sine, cosine,
      and tangent, respectively, just as they are for acute angles.
    </p>
    <remark>
      <p>
        One thing to notice is that it is not necessary to use the <em>unit</em>
        circle to define the sine and cosine functions.
        It is simply convenient.
        We see from the right-triangle definitions that any size radius will give us the same value for sine and cosine,
        provided that we take the <em>ratio</em>
        of the side lengths to the radius.
        So we could define
        <me>
          \sin\theta = \frac{y}{r}\text{ and } \cos\theta = \frac{x}{r}
        </me>
        if we choose to use a circle of radius <m>r</m>, instead of radius 1.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <p>
      Now that we have formally defined all six of the trigonometric functions,
      here is one more example of calculating the values of the trigonometric functions by hand using a reference triangle:
    </p>
    <example xml:id="ex_negative11piover4">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Sketch the angle <m>-\frac{11\pi}{4}</m> in standard position,
          and then use the unit circle to find the values of all six trigonometric functions of that angle.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Note that
          <me>
            -\frac{11\pi}{4} = -\frac{8\pi}{4}-\frac{3\pi}{4} = -2\pi-\frac{3\pi}{4}
          </me>.
          Since <m>2\pi</m> radians is one full revolution around the unit circle,
          the angle <m>-\frac{11\pi}{4}</m> opens up in the clockwise direction for one full revolution and then an additional three-quarters of the bottom half of the unit circle,
          as shown at the left:
        </p>
        <p>
          <image width="93%" source="TaalmanPage410a.png"/>
        </p>
        <p>
          In the right-hand picture above,
          we see a 45-45-90 reference triangle with the labeled side lengths of <m>\sqrt{2}/2</m>.
          Because the angle terminates in Quadrant III, both coordinates of the point on the unit circle are negative.
          By the unit-circle definitions of sine and cosine,
          <me>
            (x.y) =\left(\cos\left(-\frac{11\pi}{4}\right),\sin\left(-\frac{11\pi}{4}\right)\right)= \left(-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Therefore
          <me>
            \cos\left(-\frac{11\pi}{4}\right) =-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \text{ and }  \sin\left(-\frac{11\pi}{4}\right) =-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
